Note:
PRIORITY QUEUE - Indexable Binary Heap with MIN/MAX Ordering Tier 0 Primitive

This module provides a full-featured priority queue distinct from the
lightweight priority_queue_ functions exposed by heap.runa. It supports:

  - Independent (value, priority) entries
  - MIN-heap or MAX-heap ordering selectable at construction
  - Stable, opaque handles returned from pq_push so callers may
    update an entry's priority in O(log n) without scanning
  - update_priority that automatically sifts the entry up or down
    based on the comparison of old vs new priority
  - Geometric growth (2x) when capacity is exhausted
  - Constant-time clear that does not shrink the backing arrays

The implementation uses three parallel arrays indexed 1..size:
  priorities[i] - the signed Integer priority of the entry in slot i
  values[i]     - the caller-supplied opaque value of the entry in slot i
  handles[i]    - the handle id of the entry in slot i

A separate handle table maps handle_id -> slot_index so update_priority
can locate an entry without scanning. Handle ids are dense integers
starting from 1; a freed handle is recycled by reusing the slot index
of the last entry during swap-and-pop and by chaining the freelist
through the handle table itself when entries are popped.

Layout of priority queue header (56 bytes):
  offset 0:  priorities array pointer        (8 bytes)
  offset 8:  values array pointer            (8 bytes)
  offset 16: handles array pointer (slot->handle_id)  (8 bytes)
  offset 24: handle_table pointer (handle_id->slot)   (8 bytes)
  offset 32: size                            (8 bytes)
  offset 40: capacity                        (8 bytes)
  offset 48: ordering (0 = MIN, 1 = MAX) low 8 bits;
             handle_freelist_head in high 56 bits encoded
             via dedicated cells stored in handle_table[0]
             actually we keep ordering only here as a single int and
             store next_handle and freelist head inside handle_table
             header cells at table[0] and table[1]

The handle table itself is a self-describing structure laid out as:
  table[0]            = capacity in entries (capacity of pq + 1 reserve)
  table[1]            = next_handle (monotonically increasing handle id
                        watermark; handles below this and not on the
                        freelist are live or in the freelist)
  table[2]            = freelist_head (chain id, 0 sentinel = empty)
  table[3..]          = entry[i] for handle_id i where entry encodes
                        either the slot_index (>0) of the live entry
                        OR the next freelist link (<= 0 encoded as
                        negative chain to distinguish). Concretely:
                          live:    cell = slot_index (positive int)
                          freed:   cell = 0 minus next_freelist_handle
                                   (so cell <= 0; 0 means end of chain)
                        Handle id 0 is reserved as the null/invalid handle.

Slot indexing is 1-based; the 0th slot of priorities/values/handles is
never used as live storage so internal sift_up's parent(i)=i/2 works
without special-casing root detection.
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as Memory

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CONSTANTS
Note: ============================================================================

Let PQ_HEADER_SIZE be 56
Let PQ_INITIAL_CAPACITY be 16
Let PQ_GROWTH_FACTOR be 2
Let PQ_WORD_SIZE be 8
Let PQ_ORDERING_MIN be 0
Let PQ_ORDERING_MAX be 1
Let PQ_TABLE_HEADER_CELLS be 3

Note: ============================================================================
Note: INTERNAL HELPERS - slot addresses, handle table cells
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Address of priorities[index] given a slot index.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Returns priorities + index * 8.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Caller-validated index; no bounds check.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "pq_priority_addr" takes priorities as Integer, index as Integer returns Integer:
    Return priorities plus (index multiplied by PQ_WORD_SIZE)
End Process

@Reasoning
Address of values[index] given a slot index.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Returns values + index * 8.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Caller-validated index.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "pq_value_addr" takes values as Integer, index as Integer returns Integer:
    Return values plus (index multiplied by PQ_WORD_SIZE)
End Process

@Reasoning
Address of handles[index] (slot -> handle id mapping).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Returns handles + index * 8.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Caller-validated index.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "pq_handle_addr" takes handles as Integer, index as Integer returns Integer:
    Return handles plus (index multiplied by PQ_WORD_SIZE)
End Process

@Reasoning
Address of handle_table cell for a given handle id. The first
PQ_TABLE_HEADER_CELLS cells are reserved header (capacity, next_handle,
freelist_head); user handle id k lives at table[k + PQ_TABLE_HEADER_CELLS].
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Returns table + (handle_id + PQ_TABLE_HEADER_CELLS) * 8.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Caller-validated handle id.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "pq_table_cell_addr" takes table as Integer, handle_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Let offset_cells be handle_id plus PQ_TABLE_HEADER_CELLS
    Return table plus (offset_cells multiplied by PQ_WORD_SIZE)
End Process

@Reasoning
Read the table cell value for the given handle id. The returned cell
encodes either the slot_index (positive) for a live entry or the
freelist next link (non-positive) for a freed handle.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Computes cell address and loads the int64.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Caller-validated handle id.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "pq_table_get" takes table as Integer, handle_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Let addr be proc pq_table_cell_addr with table, handle_id
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with addr, 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Write the table cell for the given handle id.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Computes cell address and stores the int64.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Caller-validated handle id.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "pq_table_set" takes table as Integer, handle_id as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    Let addr be proc pq_table_cell_addr with table, handle_id
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with addr, 0, value
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: HANDLE TABLE LIFECYCLE
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Allocate the handle table for a given capacity. The table holds 3
header cells plus capacity + 1 entry cells (handle id 0 reserved).
The freelist begins empty; next_handle starts at 1.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1) total_cells = PQ_TABLE_HEADER_CELLS + capacity + 1
2) bytes = total_cells * 8
3) Allocate; zero all cells.
4) Store capacity in cell 0, next_handle = 1 in cell 1, freelist_head = 0 in cell 2.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(capacity).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returns 0 on allocation failure.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "pq_handle_table_create" takes capacity as Integer returns Integer:
    Let total_cells be PQ_TABLE_HEADER_CELLS plus (capacity plus 1)
    Let bytes be total_cells multiplied by PQ_WORD_SIZE
    Let table be proc allocate from Layout with bytes
    If table is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_fill from Memory with table, 0, bytes
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with table, 0, capacity
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with table, 8, 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with table, 16, 0
    Return table
End Process

@Reasoning
Grow the handle table to a new capacity. Header cells preserved;
existing handle cells copied; new cells zeroed.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1) Allocate new table of new_capacity entries.
2) Copy header (3 cells) + (old_capacity + 1) entry cells.
3) Zero remaining new cells.
4) Update header cell 0 to new_capacity.
5) Free old table; return new table pointer.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(new_capacity).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returns 0 on allocation failure (caller must still free the original
table on its own if it wants).
@End Security_Scope
Process called "pq_handle_table_grow" takes table as Integer, new_capacity as Integer returns Integer:
    If table is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let old_capacity be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with table, 0
    If new_capacity is less than or equal to old_capacity:
        Return table
    End If
    Let new_total_cells be PQ_TABLE_HEADER_CELLS plus (new_capacity plus 1)
    Let new_bytes be new_total_cells multiplied by PQ_WORD_SIZE
    Let new_table be proc allocate from Layout with new_bytes
    If new_table is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_fill from Memory with new_table, 0, new_bytes
    Let copy_cells be PQ_TABLE_HEADER_CELLS plus (old_capacity plus 1)
    Let copy_bytes be copy_cells multiplied by PQ_WORD_SIZE
    proc memory_copy from Memory with new_table, table, copy_bytes
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with new_table, 0, new_capacity
    proc deallocate from Layout with table
    Return new_table
End Process

@Reasoning
Acquire a fresh handle id. Pulls from the freelist if non-empty,
otherwise consumes the next monotonic id.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1) Read freelist_head from table cell 2.
2) If freelist_head != 0, pop it: read its cell value (which encodes
   0 - next link), restore freelist_head to that next link, return
   the popped id.
3) Otherwise read next_handle from cell 1, increment, store back,
   return the original next_handle.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returns 0 if the freelist is exhausted AND next_handle would exceed
the table capacity. Caller is expected to grow the table before
acquiring in that case.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "pq_handle_acquire" takes table as Integer returns Integer:
    If table is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let freelist_head be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with table, 16
    If freelist_head is not equal to 0:
        Let cell be proc pq_table_get with table, freelist_head
        Let next_link be 0 minus cell
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with table, 16, next_link
        Return freelist_head
    End If
    Let next_handle be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with table, 8
    Let capacity be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with table, 0
    If next_handle is greater than capacity:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with table, 8, next_handle plus 1
    Return next_handle
End Process

@Reasoning
Release a handle back to the freelist for reuse on the next acquire.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1) Read current freelist_head.
2) Write into table[handle_id] the encoded next_link = 0 - freelist_head.
3) Set freelist_head = handle_id.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Caller must pass a handle id that is no longer associated with any
live slot. Double-release would corrupt the freelist chain.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "pq_handle_release" takes table as Integer, handle_id as Integer returns Integer:
    If table is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If handle_id is less than or equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let old_head be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with table, 16
    Let encoded_next be 0 minus old_head
    proc pq_table_set with table, handle_id, encoded_next
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with table, 16, handle_id
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: COMPARISON HELPER
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Compare two priorities according to the queue's ordering. Returns
-1 if a should sit ABOVE b in the heap (i.e. closer to the root), 0 if
equivalent, 1 if b sits above a.

For MIN ordering, smaller priorities sit above. For MAX, larger
priorities sit above; we invert the sign of the comparison.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Direct comparison without subtraction to avoid signed overflow.
Invert verdict if ordering == PQ_ORDERING_MAX.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Pure function on Integer priorities.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "pq_compare" takes ordering as Integer, a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    Let verdict be 0
    If a is less than b:
        Set verdict to 0 minus 1
    End If
    If a is greater than b:
        Set verdict to 1
    End If
    If ordering is equal to PQ_ORDERING_MAX:
        Set verdict to 0 minus verdict
    End If
    Return verdict
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CONSTRUCTION / DESTRUCTION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Allocate a fresh priority queue with the requested initial capacity
and ordering. Capacity below PQ_INITIAL_CAPACITY is rounded up.
Ordering must be 0 (MIN) or 1 (MAX); any other value defaults to MIN.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1) Clamp capacity up to PQ_INITIAL_CAPACITY when smaller.
2) Allocate header (56 bytes).
3) Allocate priorities/values/handles arrays sized capacity + 1
   (so slot 1..capacity are usable; slot 0 unused).
4) Allocate the handle table for capacity.
5) Initialize all header fields.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(capacity).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returns 0 on allocation failure; cleans up partial allocations.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "pq_create" takes capacity as Integer, ordering as Integer returns Integer:
    Let final_capacity be capacity
    If final_capacity is less than PQ_INITIAL_CAPACITY:
        Set final_capacity to PQ_INITIAL_CAPACITY
    End If
    Let final_ordering be PQ_ORDERING_MIN
    If ordering is equal to PQ_ORDERING_MAX:
        Set final_ordering to PQ_ORDERING_MAX
    End If
    Let pq be proc allocate from Layout with PQ_HEADER_SIZE
    If pq is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let array_cells be final_capacity plus 1
    Let array_bytes be array_cells multiplied by PQ_WORD_SIZE
    Let priorities be proc allocate from Layout with array_bytes
    If priorities is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with pq
        Return 0
    End If
    Let values be proc allocate from Layout with array_bytes
    If values is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with priorities
        proc deallocate from Layout with pq
        Return 0
    End If
    Let handles be proc allocate from Layout with array_bytes
    If handles is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with values
        proc deallocate from Layout with priorities
        proc deallocate from Layout with pq
        Return 0
    End If
    Let table be proc pq_handle_table_create with final_capacity
    If table is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with handles
        proc deallocate from Layout with values
        proc deallocate from Layout with priorities
        proc deallocate from Layout with pq
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_fill from Memory with priorities, 0, array_bytes
    proc memory_fill from Memory with values, 0, array_bytes
    proc memory_fill from Memory with handles, 0, array_bytes
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with pq, 0, priorities
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with pq, 8, values
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with pq, 16, handles
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with pq, 24, table
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with pq, 32, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with pq, 40, final_capacity
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with pq, 48, final_ordering
    Return pq
End Process

@Reasoning
Convenience constructor for a MIN-heap priority queue.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Calls pq_create with PQ_ORDERING_MIN.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(capacity).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returns 0 on allocation failure.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "pq_create_min" takes capacity as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc pq_create with capacity, PQ_ORDERING_MIN
End Process

@Reasoning
Convenience constructor for a MAX-heap priority queue.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Calls pq_create with PQ_ORDERING_MAX.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(capacity).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returns 0 on allocation failure.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "pq_create_max" takes capacity as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc pq_create with capacity, PQ_ORDERING_MAX
End Process

@Reasoning
Destroy the priority queue, freeing all backing arrays and the
handle table.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Frees priorities, values, handles, handle_table, then the header.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1) (capacity-independent at the allocator boundary).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Caller-owned; do not pass the same pointer twice.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "pq_destroy" takes pq as Integer returns Integer:
    If pq is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let priorities be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pq, 0
    Let values be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pq, 8
    Let handles be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pq, 16
    Let table be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pq, 24
    If priorities is not equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with priorities
    End If
    If values is not equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with values
    End If
    If handles is not equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with handles
    End If
    If table is not equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with table
    End If
    proc deallocate from Layout with pq
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: STATE QUERIES
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Number of live entries.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Returns size field at offset 32.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Read-only.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "pq_size" takes pq as Integer returns Integer:
    If pq is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pq, 32
End Process

@Reasoning
Empty predicate.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Returns 1 if size == 0.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Read-only.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "pq_is_empty" takes pq as Integer returns Integer:
    If pq is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If
    Let size be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pq, 32
    If size is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Backing capacity (excludes the unused slot 0).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Returns capacity field at offset 40.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Read-only.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "pq_capacity" takes pq as Integer returns Integer:
    If pq is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pq, 40
End Process

@Reasoning
Ordering: 0 MIN, 1 MAX.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Returns ordering field at offset 48.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Read-only.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "pq_ordering" takes pq as Integer returns Integer:
    If pq is equal to 0:
        Return PQ_ORDERING_MIN
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pq, 48
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: INTERNAL SWAP - swaps slot a and b across all three arrays AND
Note: maintains the handle_table mapping for both handles.
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Swap two entries at slot indices a and b. Both their priorities,
values, and handles are swapped, and the handle_table is updated so
that the moved handles point to their new slot.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1) Load priorities/values/handles arrays and handle table.
2) Load both entries' (priority, value, handle) words.
3) Write swapped values back to slots a and b.
4) For each of the two handles, update table[handle] to its new slot.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Caller must guarantee 1 <= a, b <= size. No bounds check.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "pq_swap" takes pq as Integer, a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    If a is equal to b:
        Return 1
    End If
    Let priorities be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pq, 0
    Let values be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pq, 8
    Let handles be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pq, 16
    Let table be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pq, 24
    Let pa be proc pq_priority_addr with priorities, a
    Let pb be proc pq_priority_addr with priorities, b
    Let va be proc pq_value_addr with values, a
    Let vb be proc pq_value_addr with values, b
    Let ha be proc pq_handle_addr with handles, a
    Let hb be proc pq_handle_addr with handles, b
    Let pri_a be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pa, 0
    Let pri_b be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pb, 0
    Let val_a be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with va, 0
    Let val_b be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with vb, 0
    Let han_a be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with ha, 0
    Let han_b be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with hb, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with pa, 0, pri_b
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with pb, 0, pri_a
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with va, 0, val_b
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with vb, 0, val_a
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with ha, 0, han_b
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with hb, 0, han_a
    proc pq_table_set with table, han_a, b
    proc pq_table_set with table, han_b, a
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SIFT UP / SIFT DOWN
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Restore heap property by moving the entry at index upward while it
sits above its parent in the ordering. Stops at the root (index 1).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
While index > 1:
  parent = index / 2
  If pq_compare(ordering, priorities[index], priorities[parent]) < 0:
    swap(index, parent); index = parent
  Else: break
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(log n).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Caller must guarantee 1 <= index <= size.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "pq_sift_up" takes pq as Integer, index as Integer returns Integer:
    Let priorities be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pq, 0
    Let ordering be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pq, 48
    Let i be index
    Let keep_going be 1
    While keep_going is equal to 1:
        If i is less than or equal to 1:
            Set keep_going to 0
        Otherwise:
            Let parent be i divided by 2
            Let p_addr_i be proc pq_priority_addr with priorities, i
            Let p_addr_p be proc pq_priority_addr with priorities, parent
            Let pri_i be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with p_addr_i, 0
            Let pri_p be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with p_addr_p, 0
            Let verdict be proc pq_compare with ordering, pri_i, pri_p
            If verdict is less than 0:
                proc pq_swap with pq, i, parent
                Set i to parent
            Otherwise:
                Set keep_going to 0
            End If
        End If
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Restore heap property by moving the entry at index downward toward the
leaves, swapping with the child that sits highest under ordering.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
size = pq_size(pq)
While left = 2*index <= size:
  smallest = index
  right = left + 1
  If pq_compare(ordering, priorities[left], priorities[smallest]) < 0:
    smallest = left
  If right <= size AND
     pq_compare(ordering, priorities[right], priorities[smallest]) < 0:
    smallest = right
  If smallest == index: break
  swap(index, smallest); index = smallest
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(log n).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Caller must guarantee 1 <= index <= size.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "pq_sift_down" takes pq as Integer, index as Integer returns Integer:
    Let priorities be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pq, 0
    Let ordering be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pq, 48
    Let size be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pq, 32
    Let i be index
    Let keep_going be 1
    While keep_going is equal to 1:
        Let left be i multiplied by 2
        If left is greater than size:
            Set keep_going to 0
        Otherwise:
            Let best be i
            Let p_addr_best be proc pq_priority_addr with priorities, best
            Let p_addr_left be proc pq_priority_addr with priorities, left
            Let pri_best be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with p_addr_best, 0
            Let pri_left be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with p_addr_left, 0
            Let v_l be proc pq_compare with ordering, pri_left, pri_best
            If v_l is less than 0:
                Set best to left
            End If
            Let right be left plus 1
            If right is less than or equal to size:
                Let p_addr_right be proc pq_priority_addr with priorities, right
                Let pri_right be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with p_addr_right, 0
                Let p_addr_cur_best be proc pq_priority_addr with priorities, best
                Let pri_cur_best be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with p_addr_cur_best, 0
                Let v_r be proc pq_compare with ordering, pri_right, pri_cur_best
                If v_r is less than 0:
                    Set best to right
                End If
            End If
            If best is equal to i:
                Set keep_going to 0
            Otherwise:
                proc pq_swap with pq, i, best
                Set i to best
            End If
        End If
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: GROW - geometric capacity expansion
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Double the backing arrays' capacity and grow the handle table to
match. Used when push would overflow.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1) Compute new_capacity = capacity * 2.
2) Allocate three new arrays of (new_capacity + 1) * 8 bytes.
3) Copy existing (size + 1) entries from each old array to the new one
   (the +1 covers the unused slot 0).
4) Zero the freshly allocated tails.
5) Free old arrays; install new pointers in header.
6) Grow the handle table to new_capacity.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(size). Triggered amortized O(1) per push.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returns 0 on allocation failure. On partial failure the original
arrays remain valid (no in-place mutation occurs before all
allocations succeed).
@End Security_Scope
Process called "pq_grow" takes pq as Integer returns Integer:
    If pq is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let old_capacity be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pq, 40
    Let new_capacity be old_capacity multiplied by PQ_GROWTH_FACTOR
    Let new_cells be new_capacity plus 1
    Let new_bytes be new_cells multiplied by PQ_WORD_SIZE
    Let new_priorities be proc allocate from Layout with new_bytes
    If new_priorities is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let new_values be proc allocate from Layout with new_bytes
    If new_values is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with new_priorities
        Return 0
    End If
    Let new_handles be proc allocate from Layout with new_bytes
    If new_handles is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with new_values
        proc deallocate from Layout with new_priorities
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_fill from Memory with new_priorities, 0, new_bytes
    proc memory_fill from Memory with new_values, 0, new_bytes
    proc memory_fill from Memory with new_handles, 0, new_bytes
    Let old_priorities be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pq, 0
    Let old_values be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pq, 8
    Let old_handles be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pq, 16
    Let size be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pq, 32
    Let copy_cells be size plus 1
    Let copy_bytes be copy_cells multiplied by PQ_WORD_SIZE
    proc memory_copy from Memory with new_priorities, old_priorities, copy_bytes
    proc memory_copy from Memory with new_values, old_values, copy_bytes
    proc memory_copy from Memory with new_handles, old_handles, copy_bytes
    proc deallocate from Layout with old_priorities
    proc deallocate from Layout with old_values
    proc deallocate from Layout with old_handles
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with pq, 0, new_priorities
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with pq, 8, new_values
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with pq, 16, new_handles
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with pq, 40, new_capacity
    Let old_table be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pq, 24
    Let new_table be proc pq_handle_table_grow with old_table, new_capacity
    If new_table is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with pq, 24, new_table
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: PUSH / POP / PEEK / UPDATE_PRIORITY / CLEAR
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Insert a new (priority, value) entry into the queue. Returns the
handle id assigned to this entry. Handle ids are positive integers;
0 indicates failure (out of memory).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1) If size + 1 > capacity, grow the arrays AND the handle table.
2) new_index = size + 1
3) Acquire a fresh handle from the table.
4) Write priorities[new_index], values[new_index], handles[new_index].
5) Set table[handle] = new_index.
6) Increment size.
7) Sift the new entry up.
8) Return the assigned handle id.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(log n) amortized.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returns 0 on allocation failure or handle exhaustion.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "pq_push" takes pq as Integer, priority as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    If pq is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let size be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pq, 32
    Let capacity be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pq, 40
    If size plus 1 is greater than capacity:
        Let grow_ok be proc pq_grow with pq
        If grow_ok is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
    End If
    Let table be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pq, 24
    Let handle_id be proc pq_handle_acquire with table
    If handle_id is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let new_index be size plus 1
    Let priorities be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pq, 0
    Let values be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pq, 8
    Let handles be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pq, 16
    Let p_addr be proc pq_priority_addr with priorities, new_index
    Let v_addr be proc pq_value_addr with values, new_index
    Let h_addr be proc pq_handle_addr with handles, new_index
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with p_addr, 0, priority
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with v_addr, 0, value
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with h_addr, 0, handle_id
    proc pq_table_set with table, handle_id, new_index
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with pq, 32, new_index
    proc pq_sift_up with pq, new_index
    Return handle_id
End Process

@Reasoning
Remove and return the root entry's value (the highest-priority entry
under the queue's ordering). Returns 0 on empty queue.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1) Empty check.
2) Capture root value and root handle.
3) If size > 1, copy last entry into slot 1 (priority, value, handle),
   update table[last_handle] = 1.
4) Zero the freed last slot.
5) Decrement size.
6) Release the root handle.
7) If size >= 1, sift down slot 1.
8) Return root value.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(log n).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returns 0 on empty (caller cannot distinguish a real value of 0 from
empty without first checking pq_is_empty).
@End Security_Scope
Process called "pq_pop" takes pq as Integer returns Integer:
    If pq is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let size be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pq, 32
    If size is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let priorities be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pq, 0
    Let values be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pq, 8
    Let handles be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pq, 16
    Let table be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pq, 24
    Let v_root_addr be proc pq_value_addr with values, 1
    Let h_root_addr be proc pq_handle_addr with handles, 1
    Let root_value be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with v_root_addr, 0
    Let root_handle be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with h_root_addr, 0
    If size is greater than 1:
        Let p_last_addr be proc pq_priority_addr with priorities, size
        Let v_last_addr be proc pq_value_addr with values, size
        Let h_last_addr be proc pq_handle_addr with handles, size
        Let last_priority be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with p_last_addr, 0
        Let last_value be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with v_last_addr, 0
        Let last_handle be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with h_last_addr, 0
        Let p_root_addr be proc pq_priority_addr with priorities, 1
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with p_root_addr, 0, last_priority
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with v_root_addr, 0, last_value
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with h_root_addr, 0, last_handle
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with p_last_addr, 0, 0
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with v_last_addr, 0, 0
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with h_last_addr, 0, 0
        proc pq_table_set with table, last_handle, 1
    Otherwise:
        Let p_root_addr be proc pq_priority_addr with priorities, 1
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with p_root_addr, 0, 0
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with v_root_addr, 0, 0
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with h_root_addr, 0, 0
    End If
    proc pq_handle_release with table, root_handle
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with pq, 32, size minus 1
    Let new_size be size minus 1
    If new_size is greater than or equal to 1:
        proc pq_sift_down with pq, 1
    End If
    Return root_value
End Process

@Reasoning
Peek the value of the root entry without removing it.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1) Empty check.
2) Return values[1].
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returns 0 on empty.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "pq_peek" takes pq as Integer returns Integer:
    If pq is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let size be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pq, 32
    If size is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let values be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pq, 8
    Let v_addr be proc pq_value_addr with values, 1
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with v_addr, 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Peek the priority of the root entry (the extremal priority).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1) Empty check.
2) Return priorities[1].
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returns 0 on empty (which is also a legitimate priority - caller
should check pq_is_empty first).
@End Security_Scope
Process called "pq_peek_priority" takes pq as Integer returns Integer:
    If pq is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let size be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pq, 32
    If size is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let priorities be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pq, 0
    Let p_addr be proc pq_priority_addr with priorities, 1
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with p_addr, 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Resolve a handle to the value of the entry it identifies. Returns 0
if the handle is invalid (released or never issued).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1) Lookup table[handle]; if <= 0, return 0 (freed or never live).
2) Read values[slot].
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Caller must distinguish a real value of 0 from invalid handle by
calling pq_handle_is_valid first if needed.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "pq_handle_value" takes pq as Integer, handle_id as Integer returns Integer:
    If pq is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If handle_id is less than or equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let table be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pq, 24
    Let slot be proc pq_table_get with table, handle_id
    If slot is less than or equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let values be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pq, 8
    Let v_addr be proc pq_value_addr with values, slot
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with v_addr, 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Resolve a handle to its current priority. Returns 0 if invalid.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Symmetric with pq_handle_value but reads priorities[slot].
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Same caveat as pq_handle_value.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "pq_handle_priority" takes pq as Integer, handle_id as Integer returns Integer:
    If pq is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If handle_id is less than or equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let table be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pq, 24
    Let slot be proc pq_table_get with table, handle_id
    If slot is less than or equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let priorities be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pq, 0
    Let p_addr be proc pq_priority_addr with priorities, slot
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with p_addr, 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Returns 1 if the handle currently identifies a live entry, 0 otherwise.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
table[handle] > 0 iff live.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Read-only.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "pq_handle_is_valid" takes pq as Integer, handle_id as Integer returns Integer:
    If pq is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If handle_id is less than or equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let table be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pq, 24
    Let slot be proc pq_table_get with table, handle_id
    If slot is greater than 0:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Change the priority of the entry identified by handle. The entry is
located in O(1) via the handle table, the priority is rewritten, and
the heap property is restored in O(log n) by sifting up or down based
on how the new priority compares to the old.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1) Validate handle (table[handle] > 0).
2) Read old priority at priorities[slot].
3) Write new priority into priorities[slot].
4) verdict = pq_compare(ordering, new_priority, old_priority).
5) If verdict < 0 (new sits closer to root) -> pq_sift_up(slot).
   If verdict > 0 (new sits closer to leaves) -> pq_sift_down(slot).
   If verdict == 0 nothing to do.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(log n).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returns 0 if the handle is invalid; returns 1 on success.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "pq_update_priority" takes pq as Integer, handle_id as Integer, new_priority as Integer returns Integer:
    If pq is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let valid be proc pq_handle_is_valid with pq, handle_id
    If valid is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let table be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pq, 24
    Let slot be proc pq_table_get with table, handle_id
    Let priorities be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pq, 0
    Let p_addr be proc pq_priority_addr with priorities, slot
    Let old_priority be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with p_addr, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with p_addr, 0, new_priority
    Let ordering be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pq, 48
    Let verdict be proc pq_compare with ordering, new_priority, old_priority
    If verdict is less than 0:
        proc pq_sift_up with pq, slot
    End If
    If verdict is greater than 0:
        proc pq_sift_down with pq, slot
    End If
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Remove the entry identified by handle. Internally we sift it to the
root by giving it a sentinel best-priority then popping it.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1) Validate handle.
2) Read old priority; pick a sentinel that beats every real priority
   under ordering: for MIN we use the smallest 64-bit signed value,
   for MAX we use the largest 64-bit signed value.
3) Write sentinel; sift up to root.
4) Call pq_pop to drop the root.
5) Return 1.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(log n).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returns 0 on invalid handle.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "pq_remove" takes pq as Integer, handle_id as Integer returns Integer:
    If pq is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let valid be proc pq_handle_is_valid with pq, handle_id
    If valid is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let ordering be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pq, 48
    Let sentinel be 0 minus 9223372036854775807
    Set sentinel to sentinel minus 1
    If ordering is equal to PQ_ORDERING_MAX:
        Set sentinel to 9223372036854775807
    End If
    Let table be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pq, 24
    Let slot be proc pq_table_get with table, handle_id
    Let priorities be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pq, 0
    Let p_addr be proc pq_priority_addr with priorities, slot
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with p_addr, 0, sentinel
    proc pq_sift_up with pq, slot
    proc pq_pop with pq
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Empty the queue in O(size). All live handles are released to the
freelist so subsequent push calls reuse handle slots.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1) For slot = 1..size: release handles[slot] and zero the entry.
2) Set size = 0.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(size).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
After clear, all previously issued handles are invalid.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "pq_clear" takes pq as Integer returns Integer:
    If pq is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let size be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pq, 32
    Let priorities be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pq, 0
    Let values be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pq, 8
    Let handles be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pq, 16
    Let table be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pq, 24
    Let i be 1
    While i is less than or equal to size:
        Let h_addr be proc pq_handle_addr with handles, i
        Let handle_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with h_addr, 0
        proc pq_handle_release with table, handle_id
        Let p_addr be proc pq_priority_addr with priorities, i
        Let v_addr be proc pq_value_addr with values, i
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with p_addr, 0, 0
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with v_addr, 0, 0
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with h_addr, 0, 0
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with pq, 32, 0
    Return 1
End Process
